CHOLERA, DIARRHEA AND DYSENTERY UPDATE (03): COLOMBIA (CHOCO) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 21 Jan 2014
Source: El Pais [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
http://www.elpais.com.co/elpais/valle/noticias/tres-menores-muertos-deja-presunto-brote-colera-entre-valle-y-choco


Authorities in the Choco [department] municipality of Litoral del San Juan, close to Buenaventura [Valle del Cauca department], warned of a possible new outbreak of cholera, which has already killed 3 children in the indigenous population of Pangala. According to the mayor of the town, Oscar Rosero, the 3 children who died of suspected cholera came from the Wounaan indigenous reserve.

"We have sent a medical commission to determine the veracity of the information and, if necessary, we will declare a health emergency. There are also another 10 patients, both adults and children," Rosero said. He added that early reports indicate that the sick people presented with severe episodes of vomiting and diarrhea.

The Pangala indigenous reserve, which suffered in the 1990s from an epidemic of cholera, is located 2 hours by boat from the urban center of Litoral del San Juan on the San Juan River.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[ProMED-mail awaits more information regarding this possible cholera outbreak in an indigenous people in west central Colombia.

Choco (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choc√≥_department) is a department of Colombia known for its large Afro-Colombian population. It is in the west of the country, and is the only Colombian department to have coastlines on both the Pacific Ocean and the Atlantic Ocean. It also has all of Colombia's border with Panama.

Maps of Colombia can be seen at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/south-america/columbia-maps.html and http://healthmap.org/r/9T1Q. A map of Choco department showing the location of Litoral del San Juan can be seen at http://litoraldelsanjuan-choco.gov.co/apc-aa-files/33363731376566363830653235626435/m_Choco.jpg. - Mod.LL]
